In [[computational complexity theory]], '''LOGCFL''' is the [[complexity class]] that contains all [[decision problem]]s that can be reduced in [[logarithmic space]] to a [[context-free language]]. This class is situated between [[NL (complexity)|NL]] and [[AC (complexity)|AC]]1, in the sense that it contains the former and is contained in the latter. Problems that are [[Complete (complexity)|complete]] for LOGCFL include many problems whose [[Problem instance|instance]]s can be characterized by [[Directed acyclic graph|acyclic]] [[hypergraph]]s: * evaluating acyclic [[Boolean conjunctive query|Boolean conjunctive queries]] * checking the existence of a [[homomorphism]] between two acyclic [[relational structure]]s * checking the existence of solutions of acyclic [[constraint satisfaction problem]]s
